    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-02T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="512"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d512">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.946/425: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-02T12:00:00+07:00"
                            >May 2, 1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received May 2—7:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>303. The local press has given prominence to reported resolution introduced by
                    Senator Pittman which would authorize the President to restrict trade with
                    countries violating the Nine Power Treaty. The British Ambassador informed me
                    May 1 that the Minister for Foreign Affairs,<note n="6" xml:id="d512fn6">Wang
                        Chung-hui.</note> acting apparently on the assumption that this or a similar
                    measure will be enacted by Congress, has urged him try to introduce the British
                    Government to initiate some step by the League of Nations to bring about similar
                    action by League members. Foreign Office officials as also the British
                    Ambassador have asked me whether there is any probability that the resolution in
                    question will be adopted and I have pointed out the impossibility of making any
                    prediction.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
